Next, we can solve for the cash flow from the one-time customers. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Cash flow}&=\dfrac{\text{Quantity} \times (1-\text{Percentage of return customers})\times\text{Credit cost}}{1+\text{Required return}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Cash flow}&=\dfrac{125\times (1-0.30)\times\$7,600}{1.019}\\[15 pt]
&=\$652,600.59
\end{aligned}$$

The cash flow from non-returning customers is $\$652,600.59$
